ng them Brecht, Canetti, Seghers, Remarque, the Manns, and Ludwig Marcuse. It shows how, slowly, exile becomes a reality through the growing awareness of -- and reference to -- the exemplary figures of a shared fate. Scores of fellow travelers, from the mythic figures Odysseus and Ahasverus ("The EternalJew") to writers such as Heinrich Heine and Victor Hugo, frame the experience of exile, imbuing it with meaning, giving it depth, and even elevating it to a "High Moral Office." They frequently make appearances in the narratives of the Nazi-era exiles. The Russian-American exile poet Joseph Brodsky called writers in exile "retrospective and retroactive beings." What their retrospective gazes yield as they search for meaning in banishment is at the heart ofthis book. Johannes F. Evelein is Professor of Language and Culture Studies at Trinity College, Hartford, Connecticut.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExiles in literature. 0aExilesxHistoryy20th centuryzGermany. 0aExiles' writings, AustrianxHistory and criticism. 0aExiles' writings, GermanxHistory and criticism. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAhasverus.  aHeinrich Heine.  aNazi-era literary exiles.  aOdysseus.  aVictor Hugo.  aexemplars of exile.  aexile tradition.  aliterary testimony.  aretrospective gazes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782043270?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782043270423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782043270/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles